newsitem.title: CHINA: Shanghai soybean ends mixed on uncertainty.
newsitem.headline: Shanghai soybean ends mixed on uncertainty.

text.p: Shanghai soybean futures ended mixed on Friday due to an uncertain market trend in the absence of market-moving news, traders said.
The key November 1996 contract ended at 3,325 yuan ($400) per tonne, rising five yuan. It opened at 3,315 yuan, hitting an intra-day low of 3,310 and a high of 3,330.
January fell one yuan to 3,228 yuan per tonne, March unchanged at 3,234, May rose 90 to 3,440, July was unchanged at 3,350 and September rose 10 to 3,370.
Combined volume rose to 40,000 tonnes from 31,800.
Traders said institutions continued to liquidate their positions in the November contract and retailers remained on the sidelines.
"Most retail investors stayed on the sidelines due to a lack of market-moving news," one trader said.
"Institutions have lost interest in the November contract with the coming of its delivery date," he added.
Traders expect soybean to consolidate in a narrow range in the next few days.
